(7, 'BRASIL 2002-BRASIL', 'BRASIL 2002-BRASIL', 'brasil_2002brasil', 'brasil_2002brasil', 'VII JUEGOS SURAMERICANOS', 'VII SOUTH AMERICAN GAMES', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Fecha de apertura: 1 de agosto de 2002</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Fecha de clausura: 11 de agosto de 2002</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Los VII Juegos Suramericanos fueron realizados por primera vez en  Brasil, con las modalidades divididas en cuatro sedes: Rio de Janeiro,  S&atilde;o Paulo, Curitiba y Bel&eacute;m. De los 15 pa&iacute;ses que integran la  Organizaci&oacute;n Deportiva Suramericana (ODESUR), solamente Colombia no  envi&oacute; una delegaci&oacute;n. Antillas Holandesas, Argentina, Aruba, Bolivia,  Brasil, Chile, Ecuador, Guyana, Panam&aacute;, Paraguay, Per&uacute;, Surinam, Uruguay  y Venezuela estuvieron presentes rompiendo el r&eacute;cord de participantes:  2.069 atletas compitieron del 1&ordm; al 11 de agosto, en territorio  brasile&ntilde;o. Se disputaron 24 deportes: Acu&aacute;ticos (Nataci&oacute;n y nado  sincronizado), Atletismo, Balonmano, Boliche, Boxeo, Canotaje, Ciclismo,  Esgrima, F&uacute;tbol sala, Gimnasia (art&iacute;stica y r&iacute;tmica deportiva), Golf,  Judo, Karate, Levantamiento de pesas, Luchas, Patinaje (art&iacute;stico e  carrera), Remo, Taekwondo, Tenis, Tenis de mesa, Tiro, Tiro con arco,  Triatl&oacute;n y Vela. En los 11 d&iacute;as de competici&oacute;n, se superaron muchos  r&eacute;cordes, dentro y fuera de los escenarios deportivos. Por primera vez  un pa&iacute;s logro superar la marca de las 300 medallas. Brasil tambi&eacute;n  super&oacute; la marca de medallas de oro adjudic&aacute;ndose 148. El r&eacute;cord anterior  pertenec&iacute;a a Argentina, que conquisto 114 en los Juegos Suramericanos  del 82, en la ciudad de Rosario. Tras seis triunfos de Argentina en las  ediciones anteriores, Brasil logr&oacute; imponerse en el cuadro de medallas  con 148 de oro y un total de 333. Venezuela fue una sorpresa y termin&oacute;  segundo con 97 medallas doradas y 231 en total, superando a los  argentinos que quedaron terceros con 76 medallas de oro y 245 en total.</p>', '<p>Opening date: 1 August 2002</p>\r\n<p>Closing date: 11 August 2002,</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The VII South American Games were made for the first time in Brazil, with the modalities divided in four locations: Rio de Janeiro, S&atilde;o Paulo, Curitiba and Bel&eacute;m. Of the 15 countries that make up the organization of sports Suramericana (ODESUR), Colombia alone did not send a delegation. Netherlands Antilles, Argentina, Aruba, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Ecuador, Guyana, Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Suriname, Uruguay and Venezuela were present breaking the record of participants: 2,069 athletes competed from 1 to 11 August, in Brazilian territory. Disputed 24 sports: Water sports (swimming and synchronized swimming), athletics, handball, bowling, Boxing, Canoeing, Cycling, Fencing, football, gymnastics (rhythmic artistic and sports), Golf, Judo, Karate, weightlifting, struggles, skating (artistic and career), rowing, taekwondo, tennis, table tennis, shooting, archery, triathlon and sailing. In the 11 days of competition, overcame many records, inside and outside of the sports venues. For the first time a country achievement overcome the mark of the 300 medals. Brazil also exceeded the mark of gold medals winning 148. The previous record belonged to Argentina, which conquered 114 in the South American Games 82, in the city of Rosario. After six wins in Argentina in the previous editions, Brazil managed to succeed at the table of medals with 148 gold and a total of 333. Venezuela was a surprise and finished second with 97 golden medals and 231 in total, surpassing the Argentines who were third with 76 gold medals and 245 in total.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<a style="box-sizing: border-box; color: #128a58; text-decoration: none; cursor: pointer; outline: 0px; float: left; margin: 8px 0px 0px 