(8, 'BUENOS AIRES 2006-ARGENTINA', 'BUENOS AIRES 2006-ARGENTINA', 'buenos_aires_2006argentina', 'buenos_aires_2006argentina', 'VIII JUEGOS SURAMERICANOS', 'VIII SOUTH AMERICAN GAMES', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Fecha de apertura: 9 de noviembre 2006</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Fecha de clausura: 19 de noviembre 2006</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Los VIII Juegos Suramericanos se realizaron en Buenos Aires,   Argentina, entre los d&iacute;as 7 y 9 de noviembre de 2006. En la capital se   utilizaron 24 instalaciones deportivas, todas cedidas por clubes   privados o por los gobiernos de la ciudad y federal. En la subsede de   Mar Del Plata, 12 locales de competici&oacute;n m&aacute;s y diversas &aacute;reas de   entretenimiento completaron la infraestructura del evento. En total,   participaron 15 pa&iacute;ses: Antillas Holandesas, Argentina, Aruba, Bolivia,   Brasil, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Guayana, Panam&aacute;, Paraguay, Per&uacute;,   Surinam, Uruguay y Venezuela. Aproximadamente 3 mil atletas compitieron   en 29 modalidades: atletismo, bochas, bowling, boxeo, b&aacute;squetbol,   regata, ciclismo, hipismo, esgrima, esqu&iacute; acu&aacute;tico, futsal, gimnasia   art&iacute;stica, gimnasia r&iacute;tmica, hockey, judo, karate, levantamiento de   pesas, luchas, nataci&oacute;n, patinaje de velocidad, patinaje art&iacute;stico,   taekwondo, tenis, tenis de mesa, tiro deportivo, tiro con arco, remo,   triatl&oacute;n y vela.</p>', '<p style="text-align: justify;">Opening date: 9 November 2006</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Closing date: 19 November 2006</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The VIII South American Games were held in Buenos Aires, Argentina, between days 7 and 9 November 2006. In the capital were used 24 sports facilities, all donated by private clubs or by the governments of the city and federal levels. In the substation of Mar del Plata, 12 local competition more and various entertainment areas completed infrastructure for the event. In total, 15 countries participated: Netherlands Antilles, Argentina, Aruba, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Guyana, Panama, Paraguay, Peru, Suriname, Uruguay and Venezuela. Approximately 3 thousand athletes competed in 29 modalities: athletics, bocce, bowling, boxing, basketball, Regatta, biking, hipismo, fencing, water skiing, futsal, artistic gymnastics, rhythmic gymnastics, ice hockey, judo, karate, weightlifting, struggles, swimming, speed skating, ice-skating, taekwondo, tennis, table tennis, sport shooting, archery, rowing, triathlon and sailing.</p>', '80-buenos_aires.png', 'MEDALLERO', 'MEDAL', '81-argentina_11.png', 'http://www.odesur.org/buenos-aires-2006-argentina/', 0),
(9, 'MEDELLÍN 2010-COLOMBIA', 'MEDELLÍN 2010-COLOMBIA', 'medellin_2010colombia', 'medellin_2010colombia', 'IX JUEGOS SURAMERICANOS', 'IX SOUTH AMERICAN GAMES', '<p>Fecha de apertura: 19 de marzo 2010</p>\r\n<p>Fecha de clausura: 30 de marzo 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Los Juegos Suramericanos realizados en Medell&iacute;n, Colombia, el 2010,   establecieron un marco. Con excelentes instalaciones deportivas,  algunas  con nivel ol&iacute;mpico, el evento dej&oacute; un legado no solamente a los   colombianos. Al lado de los Juegos Panamericanos Rio 2007, el evento   represent&oacute; un gran paso en la consolidaci&oacute;n de una nueva era del deporte   en Sudam&eacute;rica. En total, participaron 15 pa&iacute;ses. Los 14 d&iacute;as de  emoci&oacute;n  registraron el n&uacute;mero r&eacute;cord de 3.637 atletas. Se disputaron   competiciones en 31 modalidades (24 ol&iacute;mpicas y siete panamericanas) en   47 instalaciones deportivas, siendo 29 permanentes y 11 temporales. Los   deportes disputados fueron tiro con arco, atletismo, badminton,   b&aacute;squetbol, h&aacute;ndbol, b&eacute;isbol, bowling, boxeo, regata, ciclismo, hipismo,   esgrima, esqu&iacute; acu&aacute;tico, f&uacute;tbol, gimnasia art&iacute;stica, gimnasia r&iacute;tmica,   judo, karate, levantamiento pesas, luchas, nataci&oacute;n, saltos   ornamentales, nado sincronizado, marat&oacute;n acu&aacute;tico, polo acu&aacute;tico,   patinaje de velocidad, remo, squash, softbol, taekwondo, tenis, tenis de   mesa, tiro, triatl&oacute;n, vela y voleibol.</p>', '<p>Opening date: March 19, 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">Closing date: 30 March 2010</p>\r\n<p style="text-align: justify;">The South American Games made in Medellin, Colombia, 2010, established a framework. With excellent sports facilities, some with Olympic level, the event left a legacy not only to Colombians. To the side of the Pan American Games Rio 2007, the event represented a great step in the consolidation of a new era of sport in South America. In total, 15 countries participated. The 14 days of emotion registered a record number of 3.637 athletes. Disputed competitions in 31 modalities (24 Olympic and Pan American seven) in 47 sports facilities, being 29 permanent and 11 temporary. The sports contested were archery, athletics, badminton, basketball, h&aacute;ndbol, Baseball, Bowling, boxing, Regatta, biking, hipismo, fencing, water skiing, football, artistic gymnastics, rhythmic gymnastics, judo, karate, lifting weights, struggles, swimming, ornamental breaks, synchronized swimming, aquatic marathon, water polo, speed skating, rowing, squash, softball, taekwondo, tennis, table tennis, shooting, triathlon, sailing and volleyball.</p>', '90-capture102.png', 'MEDALLERO', 'MEDAL', '91-medellin_11.png', 'http://www.odesur.org/medellin-2010-colombia/', 0);
