(9, 'Argentina', 'Argentina', '', '', '10-argentina.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>ARGENTINA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica independiente</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Espa&ntilde;ola o Castellano</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: Peso Argentino</p>\r\n<p>Argentina es uno de los doce pa&iacute;ses que fundo el comit&eacute; ol&iacute;mpico Internacional (COI)&nbsp; en 1894, fue parte del primer Consejo Ejecutivo por Jos&eacute; Benjam&iacute;n Zubiaur, quien se desempe&ntilde;&oacute; en ese cargo hasta 1907</p>\r\n<p>En los m&aacute;s recientes Juegos Suramericanos&nbsp; que se llevaron a cabo en Santiago de chile 2014 obtuvo el puesto 14&nbsp; con 159 medallas (46 de oro, 57 de plata, 56 de bronce)</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacado: Luis Scola jugador argentino de b&aacute;squetbol (Actualmente juega en Toronto Raptors de la NBA)</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>ARGENTINA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span>Independent Republic</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>Spanish</span> <span>or</span> <span>Castilian</span></span></p>\r\n<p><strong>Currency</strong>:&nbsp;Argentine Peso</p>\r\n<p><span><span>Argentina</span> <span>is one of</span> <span>the twelve countries that</span> <span>founded the</span> <span>International</span> <span>Olympic Committee</span> <span>(IOC</span><span>)</span> <span>in 1894</span><span>, was</span> <span>part of the first</span> <span>Executive</span> <span>Council</span> <span>Jos&eacute;</span> <span>Benjamin</span> <span>Zubiaur</span><span>, who served</span> <span>in</span> <span>that position until</span> <span>1907</span><br /><span>In recent</span> <span>South American Games</span> <span>that</span> <span>were held</span> <span>in</span> <span>Santiago de</span> <span>Chile</span> <span>2014</span> <span>it ranked</span> <span>14</span> <span>with</span> <span>159</span> <span>medals (</span><span>46</span> <span>gold</span><span>,</span> <span>57</span> <span>silver</span><span>,</span> <span>56</span> <span>bronze</span><span>)</span><br /><span>Sportsman</span> <span>highlights</span><span>:</span> <span>Luis</span> <span>Scola</span> <span>Argentine</span> <span>basketball player</span> <span>(</span><span>currently</span> <span>playing in</span> <span>the</span> <span>NBA</span> <span>Toronto</span> <span>Raptors</span><span>)</span></span></p>', 0),
(13, 'Perú', 'Peru', '', '', '20-peru.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>PER&Uacute;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Independiente</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Castellano</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: El sol.</p>\r\n<p>Las participaciones que tuvo Per&uacute; fueron importantes protagonista en Juegos Suramericanos y Panamericanos</p>\r\n<p>En Santiago 2014 40 medallas (9 de oro 13 de plata y 18 de bronce)</p>\r\n<p>El historial de medallas ol&iacute;mpicas es muy escaso, pero Per&uacute; es uno de los primeros pa&iacute;ses suramericanos en conseguir una medalla de oro en Juegos Ol&iacute;mpicos, disciplina de tiro modalidad pistola libre, con el tirador Edwin V&aacute;squez Cam</p>\r\n<p>Este deporte ha logrado tres de las cuatro medallas ol&iacute;mpicas del Per&uacute;: En 1948, en 1984 con Francisco Boza y en 1992 con Juan Giha, estos dos &uacute;ltimos de plata.</p>\r\n<p>El v&oacute;leibol le ha dado al pa&iacute;s grandes satisfacciones&nbsp; consiguiendo la medalla de plata en los Juegos Ol&iacute;mpicos de Se&uacute;l 1988</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacada: Santa In&eacute;s Melchor Huiza, es una fondista peruana. Melchor posee el r&eacute;cord sudamericano en la marat&oacute;n con un tiempo de 2:26:48. Adem&aacute;s del r&eacute;cord, Melchor es multicampeona sudamericana y panamericana de atletismo.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>PER&Uacute;</strong></p>\r\n<p><span>Independent Republic</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language</strong>: Castilian</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Currency</strong>: The sun.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Peru shares held were important player in South American Games and Pan American.<br /></span><span>In Santiago 2014 40 medals (9 gold 13 silver and 18 bronze)<br /></span><span>The history of Olympic medals is very low, but Peru is one of the  first South American countries to get a gold medal in Olympic Games,  free pistol shooting discipline mode with the shooter Edwin V&aacute;squez<br /></span><span>This sport has won three of the four Olympic medals Peru: In 1948,  Francisco Boza in 1984 and in 1992 with Juan Giha, the latter two of  silver.<br /></span><span>Volleyball has given the country great satisfaction getting the silver medal at the 1988 Summer Olympics<br /></span><span>outstanding athlete: Santa In&eacute;s Melchor Huiza, is a Peruvian fondista. </span><span>Melchor owns the South American record in the marathon with a time of 2:26:48. </span><span>In addition to the record, Melchor is South American and Pan American athletics multichampion</span></p>', 0),
(11, 'Bolivia', 'Bolivia', '', '', '30-bolivia.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>BOLIVIA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Estado Plurinacional de Bolivia</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Castellano</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: El Boliviano</p>\r\n<p>Bolivia es uno de los pocos pa&iacute;ses que ha participada de todas las versiones de Juegos Suramericanos desde la primera edici&oacute;n que se realiz&oacute; en Bolivia en 1978 en esa &eacute;poca&nbsp; Juegos denominados Cruz del Sur</p>\r\n<p>Una de las mejores participaciones de Bolivia consiguiendo medallas de oro fueron en Colombia el 2010 consiguiendo dos medallas de oro en tiro al plato con los deportistas cesar David menacho flores&nbsp;&nbsp; 2 de oro y 2 de bronce y&nbsp; Juan Carlos Pares Gacha 1 de oro y 2 de bronce.</p>\r\n<p>En la m&aacute;s reciente versi&oacute;n de los juegos que se llev&oacute; a cabo en Santiago 2014 simplemente consigui&oacute; 4 medallas de bronce.</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacado: Karen Torres Nataci&oacute;n, Estefany Coronado Marcha y Rosemary Quispe Marat&oacute;n.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>BOLIVIA</strong></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Plurinational State of</span> <span>Bolivia</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Language</strong>:&nbsp;Castilian<br /></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>Boliviano</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Bolivia</span> <span>is one of</span> <span>the few countries that</span> <span>has</span> <span>participated</span> <span>in</span> <span>all versions of</span> <span>South American Games</span> <span>since the first edition</span> <span>held in</span> <span>Bolivia</span> <span>in 1978</span> <span>at that time</span> <span>called</span> <span>the Southern Cross</span> <span>Games</span><br /><span>One of the best</span> <span>interests</span> <span>of</span> <span>Bolivia</span> <span>getting</span> <span>gold medals</span> <span>were</span> <span>in</span> <span>Colombia</span> <span>in 2010</span> <span>winning two</span> <span>gold medals in</span> <span>skeet shooting</span> <span>with athletes</span> <span>cesar</span> <span>David</span> <span>menacho</span> <span>flowers</span> <span>2 gold</span> <span>and</span> <span>2 bronze</span> <span>and</span> <span>Juan</span> <span>Carlos</span> <span>Couple</span> <span>Gacha</span> <span>1 gold</span> <span>and 2</span> <span>bronze.</span><br /><span>In</span> <span>the latest version</span> <span>of the games</span> <span>he was held</span> <span>in</span> <span>Santiago</span> <span>in April</span> <span>2014</span> <span>just</span> <span>got</span> <span>bronze medals.</span><br /><span>Sportsman</span> <span>Highlights:</span> <span>Karen</span> <span>Torres</span> <span>Swimming,</span> <span>Estefany</span> <span>Coronado</span> <span>March and</span> <span>Rosemary</span> <span>Quispe</span> <span>Marathon.</span><br /><br /></span></p>', 0),
(10, 'Paraguay', 'Paraguay', '', '', '40-paraguay.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>PARAGUAY</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Independiente</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Espa&ntilde;ol o Castellano y Guaran&iacute;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: El guaran&iacute;</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de todas las versiones de los Juegos Suramericanos y en todas las versiones de los juegos panamericanos a excepci&oacute;n de Chicago 1959 y San Pablo 1963</p>\r\n<p>La primera medalla que obtuvo fue en f&uacute;tbol masculino en los Juegos Panamericanos de Indian&aacute;polis 1987</p>\r\n<p>En su historia a&nbsp; ganado una medalla de plata (Equipos en tenis de mesa) y seis de bronce (Esteban Casarino y Carlos Caballero en squash dobles masculino, y a Benjam&iacute;n Hockin en nataci&oacute;n 200 m, estilo libre masculino, Julieta Granada Golf, la dupla Cepede/Galeano)</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacada: la Golfista Julieta Granada (medallista ol&iacute;mpica y medalla de oro en juegos suramericanos que forma parte del prestigioso LPGA Tour de Estados Unidos)</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>PARAGUAY</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Independent Republic</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>Spanish</span> <span>or</span> <span>Castilian</span> <span>and Guarani</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>Guarani</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country</span> <span>participated in</span> <span>all versions of</span> <span>the South American Games</span> <span>and</span> <span>in</span> <span>all versions of</span> <span>the Pan American Games</span> <span>except</span> <span>1959</span> <span>Chicago</span> <span>and San</span> <span>Pablo</span> <span>1963</span><br /><span>The first</span> <span>medal</span> <span>was</span> <span>won</span> <span>in</span> <span>men''s soccer</span>