(7, 'Brasil', 'Brasil', '', '', '50-brasil.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>BRASIL</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Federal</p>\r\n<p><strong>Federativa Lengua</strong>: portugu&eacute;s</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: Real brasile&ntilde;o</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de todas las versiones de los Juegos Suramericanos y Panamericanos actualmente es el n&uacute;mero 1 en el medallero hist&oacute;rico.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;En Guadalajara 2011, Brasil logr&oacute; llevarse 197 medallas, con actuaciones particularmente notables en nataci&oacute;n (85 medallas) y atletismo (60 medallas).</p>\r\n<p>Deportista Destacado: Jefinho Gon&ccedil;alves, juega actualmente en el club regastasVasca da Gama de Brasil es medio campo en F&uacute;sala</p>\r\n<p>Deportista Destacado: Rodrigo Pessoa jinete Brasile&ntilde;o ganador de la medalla de oro en salto individual en Londres 2012, hijo del tambi&eacute;n medallista de oro Nelson Pessoa.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><span><strong>BRAZIL</strong></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong></strong></span><span>Federal</span> <span>Republic</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Federal Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>Portuguese</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>Brazilian</span> <span>Real</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country</span> <span>participated in</span> <span>all versions of</span> <span>the South American</span> <span>and</span> <span>Pan American Games</span> <span>currently</span> <span>is No. 1</span> <span>in the historic</span> <span>medal</span><span>.</span><br /><span>In</span> <span>Guadalajara 2011</span><span>, Brazil</span> <span>managed to take</span> <span>197</span> <span>medals,</span> <span>with</span> <span>(60</span> <span>medals)</span> <span>particularly</span> <span>notable performances</span> <span>in</span> <span>swimming (</span><span>85</span> <span>medals)</span> <span>and athletics.</span><br /><span>Outstanding</span> <span>athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Jefinh oGon&ccedil;alves</span><span>,</span> <span>currently playing for</span> <span>club</span> <span>regastasVasca</span> <span>da Gama</span> <span>of</span> <span>Brazil</span><span>''s</span> <span>midfield</span> <span>in</span> <span>F&uacute;sala</span><br /><span>Outstanding</span> <span>athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Brazilian</span> <span>rider</span> <span>Rodrigo Pessoa</span> <span>won the</span> <span>gold medal in</span> <span>Individual Jumping</span> <span>in London</span> <span>2012,</span> <span>son</span> <span>also</span> <span>gold medalist</span> <span>Nelson Pessoa</span><span>.</span></span></p>', 0),
(1, 'Uruguay', 'Uruguay', '', '', '60-uruguay.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>URUGUAY</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Oriental</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Espa&ntilde;ol o Castellano</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: Peso Uruguayo</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de todas las versiones de los Juegos Suramericanos, su mejor participaci&oacute;n fue en Sao Paolo 1963 donde gano 12 medallas: cuatro de oro, una de plata y siete de bronce.</p>\r\n<p>En Guadalajara 2011, Uruguay envi&oacute; a 113 atletas que compitieron en 20 deportes y ganaron tres medallas de plata en pelota vasca, y medallas de bronce en vela y f&uacute;tbol masculino.</p>\r\n<p>Con 78 medallas (11 de oro, 24 de plata y 43 de bronce), Uruguay se encuentra actualmente en el puesto decimoquinto del medallero hist&oacute;rico de los Juegos Panamericanos.</p>\r\n<p>Deportista Destacado: Rodolfo Collazo, deportista uruguayo de la especialidad de Remo que gan&oacute;, entre otras medallas, medalla de oro en Buenos Aires 2006 y Medell&iacute;n 2010.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>URUGUAY</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Oriental</span> <span>Republic.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>Spanish</span> <span>or</span> <span>Castilian.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>Uruguayan</span> <span>Fart.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country</span> <span>participated in</span> <span>all versions of</span> <span>the South American Games</span><span>, her best</span> <span>Sao</span> <span>Paolo</span> <span>participation was</span> <span>in</span> <span>1963</span> <span>where he won</span> <span>12 medals</span><span>:</span> <span>four gold,</span> <span>one silver and</span> <span>seven bronze</span><span>.</span><br /><span>In</span> <span>Guadalajara 2011</span><span>,</span> <span>Uruguay</span> <span>sent</span> <span>113</span> <span>athletes competing</span> <span>in</span> <span>20 sports</span> <span>and</span> <span>won three</span> <span>silver medals in</span> <span>pelota</span><span>,</span> <span>and</span> <span>bronze medals in</span> <span>men''s soccer</span> <span>and</span> <span>sailing</span><span>.</span><br /><span>With</span> <span>78</span> <span>medals (</span><span>11 gold</span><span>,</span> <span>24</span> <span>silver</span> <span>and 43</span> <span>bronze</span><span>)</span><span>,</span> <span>Uruguay</span> <span>is currently in</span> <span>fifteenth place</span> <span>of historical</span> <span>medal</span> <span>of</span> <span>the Pan American Games</span><span>.</span><br /><span>Outstanding</span> <span>athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Rodolfo Collazo</span><span>,</span> <span>Uruguayan</span> <span>athlete</span> <span>specialty</span> <span>Remo</span> <span>won</span><span>,</span> <span>among other</span> <span>medals,</span> <span>gold medal in</span> <span>Buenos</span> <span>Aires</span> <span>and Medellin</span> <span>2006</span> <span>2010.</span></span></p>', 0),
(14, 'Ecuador', 'Ecuador', '', '', '70-ecuador.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>ECUADOR</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica independiente</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Espa&ntilde;ol o Castellano</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: D&oacute;lar Estadunidense</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que compiti&oacute; en todas las ediciones de los Juegos Panamericanos desde los primeros Juegos celebrados en Buenos Aires en 1951</p>\r\n<p>El mejor recuento de medallas para Ecuador fue en Guadalajara 2011, donde gan&oacute; 24 medallas: siete de oro, ocho de plata y nueve de bronce. Ecuador obtuvo varias medallas en atletismo, boxeo, lucha y basquetbol.</p>\r\n<p>Jefferson Leonardo P&eacute;rez Quezada (Campe&oacute;n Mundial de Marcha atl&eacute;tica 20 km en los a&ntilde;os 2003, 2005 y 2007. Medallista de oro en los Juegos Ol&iacute;mpicos de Atlanta 1996 y Pek&iacute;n 2008)</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacado: Jorge Bola&ntilde;os, medallista de oro en patinaje de velocidad sobre ruedas masculino en Guadalajara 2011.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>ECUADOR</strong></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Independent</span> <span>Republic</span><br /><strong>Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>Spanish</span> <span>or</span> <span>Castilian</span><br /><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>US dollar</span><br /><span>Country</span> <span>competed in</span> <span>all editions of</span> <span>the Pan American Games</span> <span>since the first</span> <span>Games held in</span> <span>Buenos</span> <span>Aires</span> <span>in 1951</span><br /><span>The</span> <span>best</span> <span>medal count</span> <span>for</span> <span>Ecuador</span> <span>was</span> <span>in</span> <span>Guadalajara 2011</span><span>,</span> <span>where it won</span> <span>24 medals</span><span>:</span> <span>seven</span> <span>gold,</span> <span>eight silver</span> <span>and</span> <span>nine bronze</span><span>.</span> <span>Ecuador</span> <span>won</span> <span>several medals</span> <span>in athletics,</span> <span>boxing, wrestling</span> <span>and basketball</span><span>.</span><br /><span>Jefferson</span> <span>Leonardo</span> <span>P&eacute;rez</span> <span>Quezada</span> <span>(World</span> <span>Champion</span> <span>Racewalking</span> <span>20</span> <span>km</span> <span>in 2003</span><span>, 2005 and 2007</span> <span>gold</span> <span>medalist</span> <span>in</span> <span>the</span> <span>1996 Summer Olympics</span> <span>and Beijing</span> <span>2008)</span><br /><span>outstanding athlete</span><span>: Jorge</span> <span>Bolanos,</span> <span>gold medalist</span> <span>in speed skating</span> <span>Men''s</span> <span>wheels in</span> <span>Guadalajara 2011</span></span></p>', 0),
(12, 'Colombia', 'Colombia', '', '', '80-colombia.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>COLOMBIA</strong></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Independiente</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Castellano o Espa&ntilde;ol</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: Peso colombiano</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de todas la versiones de Los Juegos Panamericanos salvo en dos, Chicago 1959 y San Pablo 1963, su participaci&oacute;n en Los Juegos Suramericanos fue irregular, su primera fue en Rosario 1982, siendo que no particip&oacute; de tres versiones en el caso de Brasil 2002 se debi&oacute; a un acto de protesta porque gracias a la guerrilla con la cual estaba enfrentada en ese tiempo los pa&iacute;ses de&nbsp; Bolivia, Chile, Paraguay&nbsp; y Venezuela amenazaron con no participar, entonces se traslad&oacute; la sede a Brasil 2002 y por este motivo no presento a su delegaci&oacute;n , luego&nbsp; fue sede de los Juegos Suramericanos en Medell&iacute;n 2010</p>\r\n<p>Su mejor participaci&oacute;n&nbsp; hist&oacute;rica fue en la m&aacute;s reciente versi&oacute;n de Los Juegos Suramericanos Santiago 2014, donde consigui&oacute; un segundo lugar con 166 medallas de las cuales 56 fueron de oro, 49 de plata, 64 de bronce.</p>\r\n<p>Colombia fue sedede Los Juegos Panamericanos en Cali en 1971</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacado: Miguel &Aacute;ngel Rodr&iacute;guez -&nbsp; Squash fue medalla de oro en los Juegos Panamericanos de R&iacute;o de Janeiro 2007, Guadalajara 2011 y Toronto 2015</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><strong>COLOMBIA</strong></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Independent Republic</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Language</strong>: Castilian or Spanish</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>: Colombian Peso</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country  participated in all the versions except Pan American Games in two,  Chicago 1959 San Pablo 1963, its participation in South American Games  was irregular his first was in rosario 1982, altogether I do not  participate in three versions in the case of Brazil 2002 it was due </span><span>a  protest because thanks to the guerrilla which was facing at that time  the countries of Bolivia, Chile, Paraguay and Venezuela threatened not  to participate, then the seat to Brazil 2002 moved and for this reason  not presented his delegation </span><span>, then it hosted the 2010 South American Games in Medellin<br /></span><span>His best historical participation was in the latest version of South  American Games in Santiago 2014, where he won second place with 166  medals of which 56 were gold, 49 silver, 64 bronze.<br /></span><span>Colombia hosted Pan American Games in Cali in 1971<br /></span><span>outstanding  athlete: Miguel Angel Rodriguez - Squash won the gold medal in the Pan  American Games Rio de Janeiro 2007, Guadalajara 2011 and Toronto 2015.</span></span></p>', 0),
(5, 'Venezuela', 'Venezuela', '', '', '90-venezuela.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>VENZUELA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Bolivariana</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Espa&ntilde;ol o Castellano</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: Bol&iacute;var</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de todas las versiones en los Juegos Suramericanos.</p>\r\n<p>El pa&iacute;s suramericano ha ganado 524 medallas, incluidas 84 de oro, 183 de plata y 257 de bronce, y se coloca en el s&eacute;ptimo puesto del medallero hist&oacute;rico los Juegos Panamericanos.</p>\r\n<p>En Guadalajara 2011, Venezuela gan&oacute; 10 medallas en levantamiento de pesas, nueve en lucha y ocho en nataci&oacute;n, ocho en esgrima y ocho en ciclismo. Hersony Canel&oacute;n gan&oacute; dos medallas de oro y una de plata en ciclismo de pista en Guadalajara 2011.</p>\r\n<p>Mar&iacute;a Simancas obtuvo la medalla dorada en atletismo en la modalidad de demostraci&oacute;n 8x800m relevo mixto internacional, siendo la primera medalla dorada para Venezuela en Juegos Ol&iacute;mpicos juveniles. (Nanjing 2014).</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacada: Fabiola Ramos, destacada deportista venezolana de la especialidad de tenis de mesa quien fue campeona de Centroam&eacute;rica y del Caribe en Mayag&uuml;ez 2010 Y campeona suramericana en Medell&iacute;n 2010.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>VENZUELA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Bolivarian Republic</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Language</strong>: Spanish or Castilian</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>: Bolivar.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country participated in all versions in the South American Games.<br /></span><span>The South American country has won 524 medals, including 84 gold, 183  silver and 257 bronze and placed seventh in the historic medal Pan  American Games.<br /></span><span>In  Guadalajara 2011, Venezuela won 10 medals in weightlifting, wrestling  nine and eight in swimming, fencing eight and eight in cycling. </span><span>Hersony Canel&oacute;n won two gold medals and a silver in track cycling in Guadalajara 2011.<br /></span><span>Maria  Simancas won the gold medal in athletics in the form of international  8x800m mixed relay demonstration, the first gold medal for Venezuela in  Youth Olympic Games. </span><span>(Nanjing 2014).<br /></span><span>outstanding  athlete: Fabiola Ramos, Venezuela''s leading specialty sportsman table  tennis champion who was Central America and the Caribbean in Mayaguez  2010 and South American champion in Medellin 2010.</span></span></p>', 0),
(3, 'Guyana', 'República Cooperativa', '', '', '30-bandera_guyana.jpg', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>GUYANA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Oficialmente reconocida como Rep&uacute;blica cooperativa de Guyana</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Ingles</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: D&oacute;lar Guyanes.</p>\r\n<p>Guyana reci&eacute;n se integr&oacute; a partir de los Juegos Suramericanos que se realizaron en Cuenca 1998, luego a participado de manera ininterrumpida de todas las versiones hasta la fecha, nunca fue sede de Los Juegos Suramericanos y Panamericanos</p>\r\n<p>Deportista Destacada: Nicolet Fernandes, destacada deportista guyanesa de la especialidad de Squash que fue campeona suramericana en Medell&iacute;n 2010 y campeona de Centroam&eacute;rica y del Caribe en Mayag&uuml;ez 2010.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>GUYANA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Officially</span> <span>recognized</span> <span>as a cooperative</span> <span>Republic of</span> <span>Guyana</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>English</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>Guyanese dollar</span><span>.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Guyana</span> <span>recently</span> <span>joined</span> <span>from</span> <span>the South American Games</span> <span>which were held in</span> <span>Cuenca</span> <span>1998</span><span>, then</span> <span>participated</span> <span>uninterruptedly</span> <span>all versions</span> <span>to date</span><span>, it has never</span> <span>hosted</span> <span>and Pan</span> <span>American Games</span><br /><span>Outstanding</span> <span>athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Nicole tFernandes</span><span>,</span> <span>outstanding</span> <span>sportsman</span> <span>Guyanese</span> <span>Squash</span> <span>specialty</span> <span>was</span> <span>South American</span> <span>champion in</span> <span>2010 and</span> <span>champion</span> <span>Medellin</span> <span>Central American</span> <span>and Caribbean</span> <span>Mayag&uuml;ez 2010</span><span>.</span></span></p>', 0),
(2, 'Surinam', 'Surinam', '', '', '120-surinam.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>SURINAM</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Oficialmente conocida como Rep&uacute;blica de Surinam antes conocida como Guayana Holandesa o Guayana Neerlandesa.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Ingles</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: D&oacute;lar surinam&eacute;s</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de los Juegos Suramericanos desde Per&uacute; en 1990 con un total hasta ahora de 7 participaciones. En el medallero hist&oacute;rico se encuentra en el puesto #13 con 21 medallas en total de las cuales: 7 oro, 3 plata y 11 de bronce. La mejor posici&oacute;n de Surinam fue en Cuenca Ecuador el 2008.</p>\r\n<p>En la m&aacute;s reciente versi&oacute;n en Santiago de chile consigui&oacute; en puesto 11 con las siguientes medallas: 1 de oro y 4 de bronce 5 en total.</p>\r\n<p>Deportista Destacado: Tosh Van Dijk taekwondista, medallista de oro en Santiago 2014.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>SURINAM</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Officially known</span> <span>as the Republic of</span> <span>Suriname,</span> <span>formerly</span> <span>Dutch Guiana</span> <span>or</span> <span>Dutch Guiana</span><span>.</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Language</strong>:&nbsp;English<br /></span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>Surinamese dollar</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country</span> <span>participated in</span> <span>the South American Games</span> <span>from</span> <span>Peru</span> <span>in 1990 with</span> <span>a total</span> <span>so far</span> <span>7</span> <span>units</span><span>.</span> <span>In the historic</span> <span>medal</span> <span>it is</span> <span>at #</span> <span>13</span> <span>with 21</span> <span>medals in total</span> <span>of which</span> <span>7</span> <span>gold</span><span>, 3</span> <span>silver and</span> <span>11 bronze</span><span>.</span> <span>The best</span> <span>position</span> <span>was</span> <span>in</span> <span>Cuenca</span> <span>Ecuador</span> <span>Suriname</span> <span>2008.</span><br />&nbsp; <span>In</span> <span>the latest version</span> <span>in</span> <span>Santiago de</span> <span>Chile</span> <span>he got</span> <span>on</span><span>&nbsp;11</span> <span>with</span> <span>the following medals</span><span>:</span> <span>1 gold</span> <span>and</span> <span>4 bronze</span> <span>5 total</span><span>.</span><br /><span>Outstanding</span> <span>athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Tosh</span> <span>Van</span> <span>Dijk taekwondista</span><span>,</span> <span>gold medalist in</span> <span>Santiago</span> <span>2014.</span></span></p>', 0),
(6, 'Panamá', 'Panamá', '', '', '130-panama.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>PANAM&Aacute;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Oficialmente reconocida como rep&uacute;blica de panam&aacute;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Espa&ntilde;ol</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: El d&oacute;lar estadunidense y el Balboa</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de los Juegos Suramericanos desde 1994 hasta la fecha la mejor posici&oacute;n fue en Santiago de chile 2014 consiguiendo el 8vo lugar en el medallero general en el hist&oacute;rico se encuentra en puesto und&eacute;cimo con 11 medallas en total de las cuales 11 fueron de oro, 14 de plata y 47 de bronce.</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacado: Irving Jahir Saladino Aranda (Ciudad de Col&oacute;n; 23 de enero de 1983) es un ex atleta ol&iacute;mpico paname&ntilde;o especialista en salto de longitud. Ganador de la medalla de oro en los Juegos Ol&iacute;mpicos de Beijing 2008. Es el segundo paname&ntilde;o en conseguir una medalla ol&iacute;mpica, sesenta a&ntilde;os despu&eacute;s de que lo hiciera Lloyd LaBeach en los Juegos Ol&iacute;mpicos de Londres 1948 ganara dos medallas de bronce en los 100 y 200 metros respectivamente. Es tambi&eacute;n el primer deportista masculino de Am&eacute;rica Central en ganar una medalla de oro.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>PANAM&Aacute;</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Officially</span> <span>known</span> <span>as the Republic of</span> <span>Panama</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language: </strong>Spanish</span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency</strong>:</span> <span>The US</span> <span>dollar and</span> <span>Balboa</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country</span> <span>participated in</span> <span>the South American Games</span> <span>since 1994</span> <span>to date</span> <span>the best position</span> <span>was</span> <span>in</span> <span>Santiago de</span> <span>chile</span> <span>2014</span> <span>getting</span> <span>the 8th</span> <span>place in the overall</span> <span>medal tally</span> <span>in the historic</span> <span>is in</span> <span>eleventh place</span> <span>with 11</span> <span>medals in</span> <span>total of</span> <span>which 11</span> <span>were gold</span><span>,</span> <span>14</span> <span>silver</span> <span>and 47</span> <span>bronze</span><span>.</span><br /><span>outstanding athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Irving</span> <span>Jahir Saladino</span> <span>Aranda (</span><span>City</span> <span>of Columbus</span><span>,</span> <span>January 23, 1983</span><span>)</span> <span>is a former</span> <span>Olympic athlete</span> <span>Panamanian</span> <span>specialist</span> <span>in long jump</span><span>.</span> <span>Winner of the</span> <span>gold medal at</span> <span>the</span> <span>Beijing</span> <span>Olympics</span> <span>2008. It is the</span> <span>second</span> <span>Panamanian to</span> <span>get</span> <span>an Olympic medal</span><span>, sixty</span> <span>years after</span> <span>Lloyd La Beach</span> <span>did</span> <span>in</span> <span>the</span> <span>1948 Summer Olympics</span> <span>won</span> <span>two bronze medals</span> <span>in the 100 and</span> <span>200</span> <span>meters</span> <span>respectively.</span> <span>It</span> <span>is also the first</span> <span>male athlete</span> <span>from Central America</span> <span>to win a</span> <span>gold medal.</span></span></p>', 0),
(20, 'Aruba', 'Aruba', '', '', '200-aruba.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>ARUBA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><strong></strong>Pa&iacute;s aut&oacute;nomo insular del Reino de los Pa&iacute;ses Bajos.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Neerland&eacute;s y papiamento.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>: el Flor&iacute;n.</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; desde la&nbsp;quinta edici&oacute;n&nbsp;de los&nbsp;Juegos Suramericanos&nbsp;que se realiz&oacute; en&nbsp;Valencia&nbsp;en&nbsp;1994. A partir de esta edici&oacute;n ha participado de manera ininterrumpida.</p>\r\n<p>Aruba ocup&oacute; su mejor posici&oacute;n en la s&eacute;ptima edici&oacute;n cuando obtuvo el duod&eacute;cimo lugar en los juegos suramericanos que se realizaron en valencia Venezuela 1994.</p>\r\n<p>Shary Albertus, Kamilah Dammers y Thashaina Seraus rompieron en un copioso llanto cuando los resultados finales de la competici&oacute;n en Bolos o Bowling confirmaron su tercer lugar, detr&aacute;s de Venezuela y Colombia, que se llevaron las medallas de oro y de plata, respectivamente.</p>\r\n<p>Deportista Destacado: Shary Albertus, Kamilah Dammers y Thashaina Seraus medasllistas de bronce en Los Juegos Suramericanos de Santiago 2014.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>ARUBA</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span>Island autonomous country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Languaje</strong>:&nbsp;Neerland&eacute;s and papiamento</span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Currency</strong>: Flor&iacute;n</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Country which participated from the fifth edition of the South American Games that took place in Valencia in 1994. From this edition has participated continuously.<br /><span>Aruba</span> <span>took his</span> <span>best position in the</span> <span>seventh year</span> <span>when he won</span> <span>the twelfth</span> <span>place in</span> <span>the South American</span> <span>Games</span> <span>which were held in</span> <span>1994</span> <span>valencia</span> <span>Venezuela.</span><br /><span>SharyAlbertus</span><span>,</span> <span>KamilahDammers</span> <span>and</span> <span>ThashainaSeraus</span> <span>broke into</span> <span>a copious</span> <span>tears when</span> <span>the final results of</span> <span>the</span> <span>competition</span> <span>or</span> <span>Bowling</span> <span>Bowling</span> <span>confirmed</span> <span>its third</span> <span>place, behind</span> <span>Venezuela</span> <span>and</span> <span>Colombia</span><span>,</span> <span>the</span> <span>gold</span> <span>and</span> <span>silver respectively</span> <span>took</span><span>.</span><br /><span>Outstanding</span> <span>athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Shary Albertus</span><span>,</span> <span>Thashaina Seraus and&nbsp;</span><span>Kamilah Dammers,&nbsp;bronze medalist</span><span>&nbsp;at the</span> <span>2014</span> <span>South American</span> <span>Games</span> <span>Santiago</span></span></p>', 0),
(8, 'Chile', 'Chile', '', '', '1000-chile1.png', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>CHILE</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>Rep&uacute;blica Independiente</p>\r\n<p><strong>Lengua</strong>: Castellano o Espa&ntilde;ol</p>\r\n<p><strong>Moneda</strong>. Peso chileno</p>\r\n<p>Pa&iacute;s que particip&oacute; de todas las versiones suramericanas&nbsp; desde Buenos&nbsp; Aires en 1951, En Guadalajara 2011, Chile gan&oacute; 43 medallas y super&oacute; as&iacute; su r&eacute;cord anterior de 41 medallas en Buenos Aires 1951. Sus tres medallas de oro incluy&oacute; su primera medalla de oro en nataci&oacute;n por KristelK&ouml;brich,</p>\r\n<p>Deportista destacado: Natalia Duco Soler es una atleta especializada en el lanzamiento de peso o Bala.</p>', '<p style="text-align: center;"><span style="font-size: small;"><strong>CHILE</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Independent Republic</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong>Language</strong><span>:</span> <span>Castilian</span> <span>or</span> <span>Spanish</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span><strong>Currency:</strong></span>&nbsp;<span>Chilean&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n<p><span><span>Country</span> <span>participated in all</span> <span>the South American</span> <span>versions</span> <span>from</span> <span>Buenos Aires</span> <span>in 1951</span><span>,</span> <span>in</span> <span>Guadalajara 2011</span><span>, Chile</span> <span>won 43</span> <span>medals</span><span>, surpassing</span> <span>its previous record</span> <span>of 41</span> <span>medals in</span> <span>Buenos</span> <span>Aires</span> <span>1951.</span> <span>His three</span> <span>gold medals</span> <span>included his</span> <span>first gold medal</span> <span>in</span> <span>swimming</span> <span>by</span> <span>KristelK&ouml;brich</span><span>,</span><br /><span>Featured</span> <span>Athlete</span><span>:</span> <span>Natalia</span> <span>Duco</span> <span>Soler</span> <span>is specialized in</span> <span>the shot put</span> <span>athlete</span> <span>or</span> <span>Bala</span><span>.</span></span></p>', 0);
